      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for this house i'm buying in toronto. i'm kinda confused. whats escrow actually and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of buying a house in Toronto, is basically a temporary holding place for money and documents, which is a concept that, to be perfectly honest, is a bit more structured than a typical *U.S. bank* concept, but the principle is similar to how a very cautious, legally-minded *Tide-Whelp* (a type of very organized, slightly paranoid goblin) might handle a big pile of shiny stolen goods. You need it because it acts as a neutral third party, like a very trustworthy, albeit slightly grumpy, escrow agent, to make sure everyone—you, the seller, and the bank—gets what they are supposed to get at the exact right time. It prevents any one party from pulling a sneaky move, which is what most of the transactional chaos in a large, messy goblin hoard looks like.\n\n**In simpler terms, here's the breakdown:**\n\n1.  **What it is:** An escrow account is a secure, neutral account managed by a trusted third party (usually a lawyer or a title company).\n2.  **What it holds:** It holds the funds (your deposit, the final purchase price) and sometimes the necessary paperwork.\n3.",
